div.p: Before/After: A20 Disabled vs Enabled Historical IBM PC Backwards-Compatibility Hack

g.text: Three A20 Enable Methods (try in order)

div.p: Address Calculation CS:IP = 0xFFFF:0x0010 = 0xFFFF 16 + 0x0010 = 0xFFFF0 + 0x10 = 0x100000 bit 20 set!
SILENT CORRUPTION Kernel loaded at 0x100000 wraps to 0x00000 Overwrites BIOS data / conventional RAM No error machine proceeds on corrupt data Crash appears far from the actual cause
Address Calculation CS:IP = 0xFFFF:0x0010 = 0x100000 bit 20 set This time: bit 20 PASSES THROUGH
CORRECT OPERATION Kernel at 0x100000 reaches extended RAM No overlap with BIOS / conventional memory Protected-mode setup proceeds safely

ol.li: Try BIOS INT 15h/0x2401 check carry flag
If failed: try fast A20 port 0x92
If failed: use keyboard controller (8042) method
After each attempt: run verification test
If all fail: halt with error (system too old/broken)

div.p: Intel 8086 (1978): 20-bit address bus max 1MB (0x000000xFFFFF) Some programs used segment wrap-around behavior (0xFFFF:0x0010 0x00000) intentionally
IBM AT (1984) / Intel 80286: 24-bit address bus 16MB 0xFFFF:0x0010 now 0x100000 (actual high memory, NOT wrap) Programs relying on 8086 wrap broke IBM needed compatibility fix

IBM's hack: Route address line A20 through the Intel 8042 keyboard controller Default: A20 DISABLED (forces wrap, 8086 compatible) OS must explicitly ENABLE A20 to access memory above 1MB This "temporary" workaround persisted for 40+ years
Bit 20 of address bus = FORCED TO 0 Hardware AND-gate on A20 line controlled by keyboard controller (8042)
A20 line MASKED bit 20 = 0 0x100000 becomes 0x000000 20-bit bus: max = 0xFFFFF (1MB)
0x000000000x0009FFFF Conventional RAM (640 KB) WRAP TARGET Write to 0x100000 lands HERE
0x000A00000x000FFFFF VGA, BIOS ROM, EBDA
0x00100000+ INACCESSIBLE with A20 off address wraps back to 0x00000
Bit 20 passes through unmodified A20 line asserted by one of 3 methods 32-bit address bus fully functional
A20 line LIVE bit 20 intact 0x100000 = 0x100000 Addresses 0x000000xFFFFFFFF accessible
0x000000000x0009FFFF Conventional RAM (640 KB) Safe kernel does NOT land here
0x000A00000x000FFFFF VGA (0xB8000), BIOS ROM, EBDA
0x001000000x07FFFFFF Extended Memory ACCESSIBLE Kernel loads here safely (127 MB usable on 128 MB system)

div.p: Reliability: Medium not all BIOSes implement it Speed: Fast (single BIOS call) When: Real mode only, before protected mode switch Error detection: Carry flag set on failure

text.tspan: ; PS/2 fast gate supported on most modern systems

g.text: in al, 0x92 ; read System Control Port A
or al, 0x02 ; set bit 1 = A20 enable
and al, 0xFE ; MUST clear bit 0 prevents CPU RESET!

div.p: Reliability: High on modern hardware Speed: Very fast (2 port I/O ops, ~200ns) Warning: Bit 0 = RESET line never set it! Origin: IBM PS/2 "fast gate A20" extension

or al, 0x02 ; set A20 bit (bit 1 of output port)

div.p: Reliability: Highest works on all hardware since AT Speed: Slow (~100s, poll keyboard status register) History: Original IBM AT method (1984) Ports: 0x60=KBD data, 0x64=KBD command/status Why KBD? IBM routed A20 through 8042 to save chip count
wait_kbd_cmd: poll 0x64 until bit 1 = 0 (input buffer empty) wait_kbd_data: poll 0x64 until bit 0 = 1 (output buffer full) Required: 8042 runs at 8MHz CPU writes faster than it processes

text.tspan: ; Check if same value appears at 0x0000:0x17FFE (= 0x07DFE + 0x10000)
; If A20 off: wrap makes them the SAME address sentinel echoes
; If A20 on: different physical addresses values differ

g.text: mov word [0x7DFE], 0x1234 ; write sentinel to low address
mov ax, [0x17FFE] ; read from +64KB (wraps if A20 off)
